Add Performance Metrics 📏
Now that we have a confusion matrix for each Probability Threshold / PPCR we can calculate the performance metrics. We will use common performance metrics that are used:
Sensitivity and Specificity are extremely popular, but you should notice that in terms of prediction they are conditional on the future.
\[
\text{Sensitivity} = \frac{\text{TP}}{\text{TP + FN}} = \frac{\text{TP}}{\text{Real Positives}} = \text{Prob( Predicted Positive | Real Positive )}
\]
\[
Specificity = \frac{TN}{TN + FP} = \frac{TN}{RealNegatives} = Prob(PredictedPositives|RealPositive)
\] A variation of Specificity is called the False Positive Rate (FPR) and it is nothing more but $$1 - Specificity$$. It’s is used in the ROC curve, but honestly I don’t think that it’s very useful. The thing that you do want to remember is that unlike Sensitivity and Specificity you want FPR to be as small as possible.
PPV and NPV might be more suitable for prediction model because they are conditional on your predictions (and you can decide now how much observations you want to predict as positives):
\[
PPV = \frac{TP}{TP + FP} = \frac{TP}{PredictedPositives} = Prob(RealPositive|PredictedPositive)
\]
\[
NPV = \frac{TN}{TN + FN} = \frac{TN}{PredictedNegatives} = Prob(RealNegative|PredictedNegative)
\]
Lift is the ratio between PPV and the Prevalence, or in other words - how much you model is better than a random guess?
\[
Lift = \frac{PPV}{Prevalence} = \frac{\cfrac{TP}{TP + FP}}{\cfrac{TP + FP}{TP + FP + TN + FN}} 
\]
Net-Benifit is (by my view) an underused metric. I think it’s a powerful way to derive Utility in a generic way. There is an assumption that says that your probability threshold in fact includes the exchange right between False Positives (FP) and False Negatives (FN).
⚠️ Warning: You don’t want to use Net Benefit based on Predicted Positives Condition Rate! If you are using Net Benefit you must declare the explicit Probability Threshold, because it is part of the components of the metric!
Another Unique think about Net-Benefit is that it can be Negative or Positive. Negative means that you’d rather not use the model at all, and Positive means that you should use the model.
Also keep in mind that this performance metric also shows if your model is well-calibrated: You’ll see that when we will compare different models how Net-Benefit varies.
Any way I recommend on reading more about this performance metric.
